        h1 assume good faith
        .background #5
        aside
          ul
            li Easy to say "Customer is so stupid they ..." / "Can't believe they've asked for ..."
            li Common to complain that they don't get back to us - but we send huge emails full of hard questions which
              | they have to fit in around their day job, so no wonder they don't feel like making a start on it
            li Maybe a meeting would be better? Or a (video?) call? We might get answers faster, and influence them to
              | be the 'right' ones
            li Assume your audience is rational. If they're frustrating, then you don't understand: communicate more!
            li Even if you can't believe it, acting as if they're reasonable will keep you calm, and help you be clearer
